sentences.sentence: From the archives As part of our Platinum 70 Year, we take a look back at AFR opinions on significant domestic and international events over the past seven decades.The divisions in the modern Labor Party, exposed by climate and coal, between its middle-class MPs and traditional blue-collar base, have a long history.
These divisions once had a sharper personal and class-conscious edge.
And a dose of reverse snobbery.

That's the significance of this Canberra Observed column by "Cato" from March 1960, commenting on the "extraordinary" upset victory of Edward Gough Whitlam in the contest for deputy leader of the federal Labor Party over working-class firebrand E. J.

That the political scene at the start of the 1960s was still shadowed by the Cold War is evident in the discussion of whether Whitlam's victory signalled Labor was moving in a more "moderate" and less "radical" direction (to say nothing of the mention of "the Groupers").

But what Cato viewed as remarkable was that a graduate of the University of Sydney, who was married to a judge's daughter and was known as "white tie and tails Whitlam", had managed to win senior office in the "workers" party.Mr Whitlam, known in some circles as "white tie and tails Whitlam", now causes one the most important upsets in the history of the Labor Party.He has been a member of Parliament for only seven years.

He is married to the daughter of Mr Justice Dovey, of NSW.He is a member of the University ClubSydney, of the Liverpool RSL Club, the Cabramatta Bowling Club, and - perhaps the most bizarre of all - of the Helensburgh Workmen's Club.Who hasn't heard of Helensburgh?He has now beaten that celebrated friend of the workers, the battler's mate, Mr E. J.

Ward, for the position of deputy leader of the Labor Party.Extraordinary.Mr Whitlam's election means, first of all, that the combination of the residual elements of the Groupers with the elements of the extreme Left - the unholy alliance which was deployed against Dr Evatt after the last federal election - is still not in a position to dominate the Caucus.

Heartening news.He was elected by a no doubt rather motley group.But narrow though his majority was, it must be taken as perhaps one of the most encouraging turns in Labor politics in recent years.His election, after such a relatively short time in Federal Parliament, must surely be interpreted as evidence of some as yet unappreciated steadiness in the Labor Party.But it would be unwise to conclude that the party has suddenly turned "moderate".Mr Whitlam may look like a "smoothy", but he sticks closely to the basic tone of the really radical thought in the party.For better or worse, Gough Whitlam likes centralised powers for the federal government, he likes "controls" and he likes government being in business.His detractors in the party, who have tried to make him out as some sort of milk-and-water radical, therefore miss the point.

He played a very significant part in the drafting of the radical report of the joint committee on constitutional review, the blueprint for the next Labor election platform.But while we may feel that Mr Whitlam has earned his just reward, there will be general sorrow for Mr [Frank] Crean, who, although he has played it rather rough with his new leader in recent weeks, has nevertheless over the last couple of years done a very solid job of opposition in Parliament.Perhaps we may be entitled to hope that when Mr [Arthur] Calwell retires Mr Crean will receive his just reward of senior office in the party.
